<exercise number="1">
    <statement>
        <p>
            Solve the system by <term>substitution</term>:
            <m>
                \begin{aligned}[t]
                2x \amp = y+7\\
                2y \amp = 14-3x
                \end{aligned}
            </m>
            <ul>
                <li><p>Step 1</p>
                <p>Choose one of the equations, and solve for one of the variables.</p>
                </li>
                <li><p>Step 2</p>
                <p>Substitute this new expression for <m>x</m> or <m>y</m> into the other equation.</p>
                </li>
                <li><p>Step 3</p>
                    <p>Notice that the new equation has only one variable. Solve the equation.</p>
                </li>
                <li><p>Step 4</p>
                    <p>Substitute the answer to Step 3 into the result of Step 1 to find the other variable. Write your solution as an ordered pair.</p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </statement>
    <answer>
        <p><m>(4,1) </m></p>
    </answer>
</exercise>

<exercise number="2">
    <statement>
        <p>
            Solve the system by <term>elimination</term>:
            <m>
                \begin{aligned}[t]
                3x+5y \amp = 1\\
                2x-3y \amp = 7
                \end{aligned}
            </m>
            <ul>
                <li><p>Step 1</p>
                <p>We choose to eliminate <m>x</m>. Multiply the first equation by <m>2</m> and the second equation by <m>-3</m>. (Why?)
                <md>
                    <mrow>\alert{2}[3x+5y=1] \amp\rightarrow \hphantom{other side of equation} </mrow>
                    <mrow>\alert{-3}[2x-3y=7] \amp\rightarrow \hphantom{other side of equation} </mrow>
                </md>
                </p>
                </li>
                <li><p>Step 2</p>
                <p>The coefficients of <m>x</m> are now opposites. Add the two equations together.</p>
                </li>
                <li><p>Step 3</p>
                    <p> Solve the new equation for the remaining variable.</p>
                </li>
                <li><p>Step 4</p>
                    <p>Use substitution to find the other variable. Write your solution as an ordered pair.</p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </statement>
</exercise>

